(
<figureCitation id="13552A62FFF8794FFD30F8C3EF34D45D" box="[659,769,1808,1832]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[192,275,1878,1900]" captionTargetBox="[316,1385,217,1844]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[310,1387,212,1844]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Phorodon humuli (Schrank). a) Apterous vivipara photomicrograph. b) Antennal segments II–VI. c) Siphunculus. d) Head and antennal segment I (left side dorsum; right side venter). e) Cauda dorsum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3710030" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3710030/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Fig. 4a–f</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="13552A62FFF8794FFCADF8C3EF4ED45D" box="[782,891,1808,1832]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="13.[192,277,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[198,1432,243,1839]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[192,1440,241,1845]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figure 5. Phorodon humuli (Schrank). a) Alate vivipara photomicrograph. b) Antennal segments II–VI. c) Siphunculus. d) Head and antennal segment I (left side dorsum; right side venter). e) Cauda dorsum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3710032" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3710032/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Fig. 5a–f</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C374656CFFF8794EFC29F8C3E995D267" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD136E7FFF8794EFC29F8C3E995D267" blockId="4.[192,1441,940,1928]" lastBlockId="5.[192,1441,217,1928]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
is the hop aphid, adventive and widespread in North America at least since 1863 (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFF4B16FFF8794FFD38F8E3EF4BD43D" author="Foottit, R. G. &amp; S. E. Halbert &amp; G. L. Miller &amp; E. Maw &amp; L. M. Russell" box="[667,894,1840,1864]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="583 - 610" refId="ref5489" refString="Foottit, R. G., S. E. Halbert, G. L. Miller, E. Maw, and L. M. Russell. 2006. Adventive aphids (Hemiptera: Aphididae) of America north of Mexico. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 108: 583 - 610." type="journal article" year="2006">Foottit et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). Apterae of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D64FFF8794FFBBEF8E2E8ACD43D" baseAuthorityName="Schrank" baseAuthorityYear="1801" box="[1053,1177,1840,1864]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Phorodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="humuli">
<emphasis id="B91AEAF5FFF8794FFBBEF8E2E8ACD43D" box="[1053,1177,1840,1864]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">P. humuli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D64FFF8794FFECBF882EDC2D41D" box="[360,503,1872,1896]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Phorodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cannabis">
<emphasis id="B91AEAF5FFF8794FFECBF882EDC2D41D" box="[360,503,1872,1896]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">P. cannabis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of flabellate setae and by shorter setae on antennal segment III (
<figureCitation id="13552A62FFF8794FFF53F8A3ED71D4FD" box="[240,324,1904,1928]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="10.[192,275,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[201,1423,215,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[192,1440,200,1825]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 2. Phorodon cannabis Passerini. a) Apterous vivipara photomicrograph. b) Antennal segments II–VI. c) Siphunculus. d) Head and antennal segment I (left side dorsum; right side venter). e) Cauda dorsum. f) Enlargement of dorsal abdominal spatulate setae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3710026" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3710026/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Fig. 2b</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="13552A62FFF8794FFE22F8A3ED94D4FD" box="[385,417,1904,1928]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[192,275,1878,1900]" captionTargetBox="[316,1385,217,1844]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[310,1387,212,1844]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Phorodon humuli (Schrank). a) Apterous vivipara photomicrograph. b) Antennal segments II–VI. c) Siphunculus. d) Head and antennal segment I (left side dorsum; right side venter). e) Cauda dorsum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3710030" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3710030/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">4b</figureCitation>
). This species is common and damaging on hops in North America, especially in the Pacific Northwest and is not known from 
<emphasis id="B91AEAF5FFF9794EFD73FF0AEF70D384" box="[720,837,217,241]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Cannabis</emphasis>
. The aphids overwinter on 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D64FFF9794EFB00FF09E8C8D384" box="[1187,1277,218,241]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Prunus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91AEAF5FFF9794EFB00FF09E8C8D384" box="[1187,1277,218,241]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Prunus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, particularly ornamental purple leaf plum, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D64FFF9794EFD8DFF29EF7ED267" authority="Ehrh" authorityName="Ehrh" box="[558,843,250,274]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Prunus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cerasifera">
<emphasis id="B91AEAF5FFF9794EFD8DFF29EF30D267" box="[558,773,250,274]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Prunus cerasifera</emphasis>
Ehrh
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D64FFF9794EFCF9FF29EFF9D267" box="[858,972,250,274]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
) (S. E. Halbert, personal observation).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
